{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488468"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:43:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:43:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"452"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/452"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.14,0.07,0.07,0.51]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"452"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107261"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/452"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"452"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89720"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2924"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2586"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2851"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12205"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14654"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18453"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38415"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107261","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107261"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 56-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two month history of right-sided flank pain. The pain is intermittent and nothing seems to make it better or worse. He does not have any changes in bowel motions, blood in his stool, nausea, vomiting, or fever. On examination, vitals are within normal limits and no other abnormalities are found. A non-contrast CT scan is performed (Image: All the stones are \u0026lt;2 cm diameter).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Percutaneous nephrolithotomy","Ureteroscopic extraction","Stent placement","Potassium citrate alkanisation of the urine","Extracorporeal shockwave lithotripsy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a classic history of renal colic due to kidney stones. The CT scan shows three stones in the right renal collecting system. There is no hydronephrosis. Treatment of this patient\u0027s kidney stones can be carried out on an elective basis. All the stones are less than 2 cm diameter and thus would be suitable for \u003Cstrong\u003Eextracorporeal shockwave lithotripsy\u003C/strong\u003E. This technique is well suited for small stones situated in the upper and middle calyces.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEmergency decompression of kidney stones (\u003Cstrong\u003Eureteric stent\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eureteroscopic extraction\u003C/strong\u003E) is required when one or more of the following is present:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Erenal function is impaired\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ethere is evidence of infection as a result of the obstruction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Epain is ongoing and uncontrolled despite adequate pain relief\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ethe patient only has one kidney.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStones in the lower calyces and those 1-2 cm diameter can be approached with ureteroscopic lithotripsy. i.e. they would need to be fragmented first and then the small fragments retrieved using the ureteroscope and a stone basket. \u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous nephrolithotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the preferred approach for stones larger than 2 cm diameter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPotassium citrate\u003C/strong\u003E is prescribed as a preventative measure in patients who are at risk of recurring kidney stones, not as a treatment for current kidney stones.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In patients with small, non-emergent kidney stones, extracorporeal shockwave lithotripsy is first-line management.","Features of kidney stones requiring emergent intervention include 1. evidence of infection 2. impaired renal function, 3. uncontrolled pain and 4. only one kidney."],"references":["Rule AD, Lieske JC, Pais VM Jr. Management of Kidney Stones in 2020. JAMA. 2020 May 19;323(19):1961-1962. doi: 10.1001/jama.2020.0662. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32191284/","Assimos D, Krambeck A, Miller NL, Monga M, Murad MH, Nelson CP, et al. Surgical Management of Stones: American Urological Association/Endourological Society Guideline, PART II. J Urol. 2016 Oct;196(4):1161-9. doi: 10.1016/j.juro.2016.05.091. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27238616/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89720"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"452"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17148"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17148","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17148"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2afb4315-f2ac-46ef-9dae-f1ca91682727.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2afb4315-f2ac-46ef-9dae-f1ca91682727.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":625,"height":475}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89720","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89720"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-27T08:05:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-27T08:06:39+09:30"},"relationship